Model fitting

julia> model = pcasvd(nlv = 10)
Jchemo.JchemoModel{typeof(Jchemo.pcasvd), Base.Pairs{Symbol, Int64, Tuple{Symbol}, @NamedTuple{nlv::Int64}}}(Jchemo.pcasvd, nothing, Base.Pairs(:nlv => 10))

julia> fit!(model, X)

julia> @names model
(:algo, :fitm, :kwargs)

julia> fitm = model.fitm ;

julia> @names fitm
(:T, :V, :sv, :xmeans, :xscales, :weights, :niter, :par)

Scores T

The scores are already computed and returned in sub-object fitm 

julia> @head T = fitm.T

 -1.74085  -1.25003  -0.0913075  …  -0.0120857   0.0234582  -0.0483602

but can also be computed by projecting the data on the loadings (more generally, this projection is done to compute the scores of new data not used in the model fitting)

2-D score spaces

For instance, the space PC1-PC2 can be plotted by

julia> plotxy(T[:, 1], T[:, 2]; zeros = true, xlabel = "PC1", ylabel = "PC2").f

More information (recommended in practice) can be displayed using function plotlv

julia> plotlv(T[:, 1:6]; shape = (2, 3), color = (:blue, .5), zeros = true, xlabel = "PC", 
           ylabel = "PC").f

See functions plotxy and plotlv for more options.

3-D score spaces

3D representations of the score space are often more informative than 2D representations, especially when using interactive axe-rotation.

julia> CairoMakie.activate!()  
       #GLMakie.activate!()    # for interactive axe-rotation

julia> i = 1
1

julia> size = (600, 350)
(600, 350)

julia> plotxyz(T[:, i], T[:, i + 1], T[:, i + 2]; size, color = (:red, .3), markersize = 10, 
           xlabel = string("PC", i), ylabel = string("PC", i + 1), zlabel = string("PC", i + 2), 
           title = "Pca score space").f

See function plotxyz for more options.
